<p class="fnline"><a class="footnotebody" href="anonymous-the-anarchism-of-the-other-person#fn_back40" id="fn40">[40]</a> Perhaps Levinas’ phenomenology of conversation can be most clearly observed in an internet chat room, in which one party makes a statement, forever etched in memory, but retains the possibility to respond in ways that can not be anticipated.
</p>

<p class="fnline"><a class="footnotebody" href="anonymous-the-anarchism-of-the-other-person#fn_back41" id="fn41">[41]</a> Levinas, <em>Totality</em>, 129. Alphonso Lingis’ strategy of capitalizing “Other” in his translations unfortunately obscures the relationships between the human Other and the elemental Other.
</p>

<p class="fnline"><a class="footnotebody" href="anonymous-the-anarchism-of-the-other-person#fn_back42" id="fn42">[42]</a> Levinas, <em>Totality</em>, 66-67. In <em>Otherwise Than Being</em>, Levinas similarly describes responsibility for the Other as something that affects the self anarchically, prior to its own identity “slipping into me like a thief.” (p. 13, 148, 150)
</p>

<p class="fnline"><a class="footnotebody" href="anonymous-the-anarchism-of-the-other-person#fn_back43" id="fn43">[43]</a> Levinas, <em>Totality</em>, 46.
